I'm assuming from your posts you are some type of officer!??  If so how would your department react to this situation?<br>
<br>
You are off duty, you witness a Shooting, the victim is cared for by other witness, the Police/emergency personal are in route, the shooter is fleeing in vehicle.  (In my area the average response times are about 5 mins, as I live in a very rural area, we have no city police, and only a Sheriff for county duties, we rely heavily on the State Police)  The chance of this guy getting away if you don't move will be high, do you follow and try to apprehend? Do you say &quot;I'm off duty, sorry&quot;<br>
<br>
As a good cop I am going to assume you do the right thing and pursue, during pursuit you are shot. Should you be covered?  Again in my area ALL Police are REQUIRED to intervene because of the remoteness, also if you sat by and let this shooter get away imagine the public out cry, not to mention if the victim dies.  <br>
<br>
I say this because it has happened out here, The state deemed that because of the nature of the job the officer was &quot;Always&quot; on duty, and there for obligated to intervene, and hence the state obligated to cover the medical bills.<br>
<br>
This is also a fact for the Military, there is No such thing as &quot;Off Duty&quot; you may not be required be in uniform, but you are expected to offer the proper respects, and considerations to the officers, men/women, and or units you serve with.  I can remember Many a time getting pulled aside for not saluting an officer while he was in uniform and I was not, or getting into shit for not paying the proper respect to the flag at close of day...<br>
<br>
Now maybe this guys city is different, maybe there are close enough that they have a good response time, but he is a cop, he is on duty at all times, I am not saying the paper pusher in the district court house should get the same considerations as any of the police as they don't have the same responsibilities to the community.  This can be said for Fire fighters as well - imagine a building on fire and a little girl caught on a second floor yelling out the window, and this off duty fire fighter standing by and JUST watching, the wrath of shit that he and his department would receive!!!!<br>
<br>
Maybe the city should not cover it out of their pockets, but they should at least have some sort of EXTRA insurance, fund, and system for just such an event.<br>
<br>
As for the caring of cops and the reason they become cops, all the cops I know pretty much say it's the thought of helping people, but then it's also the POWER to do something about the problems they see.... <br>
